Class Piece

java.lang.Object
  Piece

public abstract class Piece
extends java.lang.Object

Piece is the superclass for all of your pieces (like Rooks, or Knights). This is completely implemented, and need not be changed.

checkMove

protected abstract boolean checkMove(Location toSpot)
A useful and suggested function for checking if moving to toSpot is a legal move for that Piece. If you don't wnat to use this, take it out.

Parameters:
toSpot - The Location to move to.
Returns:
true if moving to toSpot from the field loc is a legal move for this piece, false otherwise.

mustBeOpen

public abstract Location[] mustBeOpen(Location toSpot)
                               throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Add for Step 4. Returns an array of Locations that must all be open for the move to be legal, because most pieces (except Knight) cannot "jump" another Piece to make a move.

Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException

makeMove

public abstract boolean makeMove(Location toSpot)
Move the piece from its current location to the input location. If this is a legal move, and the move was successful, then it should return true.

Parameters:

Returns:
true if moving to toSpot from the field loc is a legal move for this piece, false otherwise.

toString

public abstract java.lang.String toString()
Print out the Unicode character for this chess piece. Those can be found here, in the "Codepoint" column. To print out a specific unicode character, you have to escape it with a backslash, much like you must for a newline character (\n). As an example, for King, which has unicode values 2654 (for white) and 265a (for black) you might do: 
   String s;
   if (color==Piece.WHITE)
     s="\u2654";
   else
     s="\u265a";
   return s;

Overrides:
toString in class java.lang.Object
